g.text: Can compile to Prolog and thus
Daniel P. Friedman, William E. Byrd
One can reason about the system's capabilities in terms of the
(fragment of) logic it is based on and the logic's models (if the
- Soundness (proves nothing which is labeled FALSE by the logic)
- Completeness (proves everything which is labeled TRUE by the logic)
- Consistency (doesn't label a sentence both TRUE and FALSE)
- Tractability: Keeps the combinatorial explosion in check
To allow tractability, the system's capabilities must be much reduced.
No compiler checks of moding or type checks
Many systems are built "on top of" Prolog,
making it the assembly language of LP
